y. While Fournier believes that sovereignty for Quebec has recently become a more realistic option, he shows that many obstacles remain. Among these are the division, contrary to popular belief, of Quebec's business class on the issue and the preference of Bourassa's government for a renewed federalism. The response of the rest of Canada to Quebec's new constitutional initiatives, Fournier maintains, will have considerable influence on how far down the road to sovereignty Quebec may choose to travel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFederal governmentxCanada. 0aFederal governmentzCanada. 0aFederal-provincial relationsxQuébec (Province). 0aFédéralismexCanada. 0aRelations fédérales-provinciales (Canada)xQuébec (Province). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh1 aFischman, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359277340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773592773423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773592773/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles